cessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOrganized labor faces enormous challenges in the increasingly global economy. The effect of multinational corporations, the portability of technology and capital, and lowered trade barriers in international commerce have all sparked widespread prophecies of trade union demise. This book, however, presents compelling evidence that unions can survive and grow if labor is willing to cooperate across national borders. Transnational Cooperation among Labor Unions is a seminal study of such cooperation as an effective weapon against the exploitation of workers in today's world.After assessing the challenges confronting organized labor, the authors turn their attention to specifics. They describe and evaluate the most important transnational labor associations, campaigns, and transnational cooperatives in a variety of industries. Contributors include academics who have assessed the status of union-management relations and international labor organizations as well as participants in union campaigns organized across national boundaries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aInternational labor activities. 0aLabor unions. 4aInternational Studies. 4aLabor History. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh1 aAnner, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Larry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEarly, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGordon, Michael A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGordon, Michael E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJessup, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabula